liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It was almost a carbon copy of Caitlin Foord's goal from the Denmark game, with Katrina Gorry unleashing Kerr with a ball over the top and the Matildas captain one-on-one with England goalkeeper Mary Earps. But her left-foot strike was straight into Earps's legs from the angle. And the linesperson already had her offside. She just mistimed the run and it was a pretty easy call.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 7' Sam Kerr misses a golden opportunity, but she's offside anyway

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: England has won every one of its matches at this tournament. The Lionesses were one of three teams, along with Sweden and Japan, to go 3-0 in the group stage, although it started with a surprisingly challenging 1-0 win over Haiti. The European champions beat Denmark by the same scoreline before rolling China 6-1 in a performance more akin to what we've come to expect from them. Nigeria pushed them to the brink in the round of 16, with England prevailing 4-2 in a penalty shootout, and then had to come back from 1-0 down to beat Colombia 2-1 in Saturday's quarterfinal.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: How England got here

props.alt: England player holds her neck while surrounded by Nigeria players at the FIFA Women's World Cup.

children.content: England has won every one of its matches at this tournament.
The Lionesses were one of three teams, along with Sweden and Japan, to go 3-0 in the group stage, although it started with a surprisingly challenging 1-0 win over Haiti.
The European champions beat Denmark by the same scoreline before rolling China 6-1 in a performance more akin to what we've come to expect from them.
Nigeria pushed them to the brink in the round of 16, with England prevailing 4-2 in a penalty shootout, and then had to come back from 1-0 down to beat Colombia 2-1 in Saturday's quarterfinal.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Remember the France game ? After 90 minutes, plus half an hour of extra time, it took 20 penalties — a Women's World Cup record — to get a winner in Brisbane on Saturday in a truly iconic moment in Australian sporting history. That also means the Matildas have played their longest match just before a four-day turnaround into this semifinal. The previous matches were a 1-0 win over Ireland thanks to a dubious penalty, a 3-2 loss to Nigeria, a 4-0 drubbing of Olympic champions Canada, and a dominant 2-0 victory over Denmark in the round of 16.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: How the Matildas got here
